'ExpressAfrica is an online social media, that helps to interconnect all Africans and share their culture, customs, belief, religion, language. This program has also a mission to register African known cultures, customs, languages, cultural heritages and known people in all Africa and the world. ExpressAfrica was launched on June, 2019. It is organized to give peoples the power to build community and access online stores across Africa and the world . ExpressAfrica is licensed under Ethiopian Intellectual property office. African People should be heard and to have a voice. They have a lot of different cultures, languages, beliefs, religions that are not shared each other. They also have more or less similar heritages, amazing places that should be told to the world. Due to lack of organizers and less sound for it, they cannot interact and share what they have and announce it to the world. As we identify this (lack of organizers and less sound for it) as a one major problem, we decided to start and African social media called ExpressAfrica. Any one who is interested to join ExpressAfrica can join at any time with free of charge, share what they want to share and leave the membership at anytime they need.' The major Climate-Related Challenges in Tigray in relation to climate change include:  1. Irregular and Insufficient Rainfall: Tigray is experiencing highly variable rainfall during this rainy season, with many parts of Tigray not receiving adequate precipitation.  2. Desert Locust Swarm: A widespread desert locust swarm has been reported in many districts of Eastern Tigray, suspected to have originated from the neighboring Afar region. Crops have been highly affected by the infestation in addition to the the water stress. This poses a significant threat to agricultural productivity and food security.  3. Beetle Infestation: Beetles attacking Celtis Africana, locally known as Qawa, trees have been observed in various forest patches, leading to tree damage and potential ecosystem disruption.  4. Pests: Pests and disease have become rampant in most parts of Tigray in a magnitude never seen before. The Cactus Opuntia, locally named as Beles, known for its delicious fruit and as livestock feed, has been severely impacted by the Cochineal insect (Dactylopius coccus). A number of other pests have been reported to have caused devastation to the already moisture and nutrient deprived crops in many parts of Tigray.  5. Armed Conflict Amplified by Climate Change: The devastating armed conflict in the region, coupled with the effects of climate change, has exacerbated environmental and socioeconomic problems, requiring global attention and potential research intervention.  These climate-related challenges highlight the area as a hot spot for climate and environmental research to bring about sustainable solutions.

The only official language of Ethiopia is Amharic. The national languages of Eritrea are Tigrinya and Arabic.
